📊 Security Group vs Network ACL

| Feature       | Security Group        | Network ACL                |
|---------------|-----------------------|----------------------------|
| Level         | EC2 Instance          | Subnet                     |
| Type          | Stateful              | Stateless                  |
| Rules         | Allow Only            | Allow & Deny               |
| Return Traffic| Automatically Allowed | Must be Explicitly Allowed |
| Evaluation    | All Rules             | Rule Number Order          |


 🎯 Key Learning
- Security Groups protect individual EC2 instances.
- Network ACLs protect entire subnets.
- Security Groups are **stateful**.
- NACLs are **stateless**.
- Both work together to provide layered security in AWS.

To understand NACL clearly:
In NACL, Inbound rules: The traffic is checked in ascending order i.e. if application is on port 8000 but you have defined as below:

Role number      type           protocol   port range   source        Allow/Deny
100             custom tcp       TCP(6)     8000         0.0.0.0/0      Deny
200              All traffic      All        All         0.0.0.0/0       Allow

Since NACL goes by Ascending order of role no i.e. first 100 is checked and then goes to 200 even though in 200 role no. you are allowing all traffic but in 100 port: 8000 is denied and application wont be accesible to the external user. this way a devops engg can make the applicattion secure.
